 films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:2010s sequel films]]\n[[Category:2010s superhero films]]\n[[Category:American films about revenge]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:Drone films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about technological impact]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jon Favreau]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Debney]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2010]]\n[[Category:Films set in California]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films set in Malibu, California]]\n[[Category:Films set in Monaco]]\n[[Category:Films set in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Films set in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films set in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Monaco]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films using computer-generated imagery]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Justin Theroux]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Iron Man (film series)]]\n[[Category:Marvel Cinematic Universe films]]\n[[Category:Motion capture in film]]\n[[Category:American science fiction adventure films]]\n[[Category:Sequel films]]\n", "name_user": "Favre1fan93", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron_Man_2"}
{"title_page": "Marjorie Herrera Lewis", "text_new": "'''Marjorie Herrera Lewis''' (born 1957) is a [[sports journalist]] best known for her 2018 novel ''When the Men Were Gone''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/espnw/voices/article/25088348/ode-barrier-breakers-hidden-figures-firsts-football|title=Marjorie Herrera Lewis on the legacy of Tylene Wilson|date=October 26, 2018|website=ESPN.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://footballfoundation.org/news/2017/11/9/_96.aspx|title=Marjorie Herrera Lewis Continuing Historic Season as Only Woman Assistant Coach In College Football For Texas Wesleyan Rams|website=National Football Foundation}}</ref> In 2018, the book was selected by [[Sports Illustrated]] as one of the best sports books in its year-in-review issue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/entertainment/author-credits-tu-shirt-for-prompting-historical-novel/article_5437c374-84c0-5289-a638-486a36833bc1.html|title=Author credits TU shirt for prompting historical novel|first=Kelly Hines Tulsa|last=World|website=Tulsa World}}</ref> In 2017, at age 60, Lewis coached defensive backs at [[Texas Wesleyan University]], making her the only female college football coach at any level that year.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fortworthbusiness.com/news/briefs/toughing-it-out-texas-wesleyan-female-football-coach-takes-the/article_6fb7b0c0-cfd6-11e7-a1e5-4bda2f40a533.html|title=Toughing it out: Texas Wesleyan female football coach takes the field|first=Rick Mauch FWBP|last=Correspondent|website=Fortworthbusiness.com}}</ref> In 1984, Lewis joined the [[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]] and later became the first female beat writer to cover the [[Dallas Cowboys]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldbanner.com/sports/sports-views-marjorie-herrera-lewis-is-a-pioneer-in-texas/article_629521f8-8bd6-11e9-9c55-dbc4d39e7247.html|title=Sports Views: Marjorie Herrera Lewis is a pioneer in Texas football|first=David Claybourn &#124; Herald-Banner Sports|last=Editor|website=Herald-Banner}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBorn and raised in [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]], Lewis was the second of five children. Her father is a retired dentist, and her mother is a retired accountant. In 1975, Lewis graduated from St. Michael\u2019s High School in Santa Fe, where she competed in basketball, softball, flag football, tennis, and volleyball.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.krqe.com/news/mornings/former-santa-fe-local-tastes-success-with-novel/|title=Former Santa Fe Local Tastes Success with Novel|date=October 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.assignmentmag.com/onlineonly/2018/10/31/qtvdany5zta6k59ndii2sr89nbknkp|title=AUTHOR SPOTLIGHT: Marjorie Herrera Lewis|website=ASSIGNMENT}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nLewis holds a BS from [[Arizona State University]], an MA from [[The University of Texas at Arlington]], and an MFA from [[Southern New Hampshire University]]. Lewis also has certificates from [[Southern Methodist University]] and [[Cornell University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://marjorieherreralewis.com/author|title=When The Men Were Gone|first=When The Men Were|last=Gone|website=When The Men Were Gone}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://andreasomberg.com/aslitagent/project/marjorie-herrera-lewis/|title=Marjorie Herrera Lewis &#124; Andrea Somberg: Literary Agent}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n\n== Career ==\nLewis was the sports editor for the [[Kilgore News Herald]] from 1983 to 1984.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kilgorenewsherald.com/lifestyles/former-kilgore-news-herald-sports-editor-jumps-into-literary-world/article_26099ed2-c072-11e9-8ba7-d3dd71cadfa9.html|title=Former Kilgore News Herald sports editor jumps into literary world|first=LUCAS STROUGH|last=lstrough@kilgorenewsherald.com|website=Kilgore News Herald}}</ref> In 1984, Lewis became the first woman hired as a sports writer at the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. In 1986, she became the first woman assigned to the Dallas Cowboys beat.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dmagazine.com/publications/d-magazine/2018/december/how-a-female-sportswriter-went-from-covering-to-coaching-football/|title=How a Female Sportswriter Went From Covering to Coaching Football}}</ref> Lewis started writing for [[The Dallas Morning News]] in 1989.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldbanner.com/news/lifestyles/former-sportswriter-in-greenville-may-to-discuss-her-book-on/article_5c0e929c-8195-11e9-b469-f7eb632cec9c.html|title=Former sportswriter in Greenville May 29 to discuss her book on a Texas legend: WWII-era female football coach|first=Alice Reese &#124; Herald-Banner A&E|last=Writer|website=Herald-Banner}}</ref> During her career with the Fort Worth Star-Telegram and The Dallas Morning News, Lewis covered the Dallas Cowboys, the [[Dallas Mavericks]], the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]], and the [[Davis Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://txwes.edu/academics/artsletters/undergraduate-majors/mass-communication/marjorie-herrera-lewis-endowed-speaker-series/|title=Marjorie Herrera Lewis Endowed Speaker Series - Texas Wesleyan University|website=txwes.edu}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Lewis joined the coaching staff of the Texas Wesleyan University football team in [[Fort Worth, Texas]].<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.houstonpublicmedia.org/articles/shows/houston-matters/2018/11/28/313229/how-a-texas-woman-saved-high-school-football-when-the-men-were-gone/|title=How A Texas Woman Saved High School Football \u2018When The Men Were Gone\u2019|first=Michael|last=Hagerty|date=November 28, 2018|website=Houston Public Media}}</ref><ref>https://www.star-telegram.com/sports/college/football/article100303427.html</ref>\n\nLewis is co-editor of ''SportsDay Bound'' (second edition, [[Abilene Christian University Press]], 2018), a collection of sports stories published by The Dallas Morning News.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nLewis wrote ''When the Men Were Gone'' ([[William Morrow and Company|William Morrow]], an imprint of [[HarperCollins]]), which [[Newsweek]] included on its list of Best Books of 2019 So Far.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/best-books-2019-so-far-21-fiction-nonfiction-and-poetry-picks-read-memorial-1435723|title=Best Fiction, Nonfiction and Poetry of 2019 thus far: What to read before Summer starts|first=Kelly Wynne On 5/26/19 at 12:10 AM|last=EDT|date=May 26, 2019|website=Newsweek}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snhu.edu/about-us/newsroom/2019/08/marjorie-herrera-lewis?fbclid=IwAR2rWC8Jem3eAc-CT9p8C6Ab05C2TxHNOmbVa6tn77KJvXE-sIIpHtFDVYw|title=Q&A with Sports Journalist, Novelist Marjorie Herrera Lewis '16MFA|website=www.snhu.edu}}</ref> The book was released on October 2, 2018. The historical fiction novel is based on the life of Tylene Wilson, a teacher and assistant principal in [[Brownwood, Texas]] during [[World War II]], who volunteered to coach the [[Daniel Baker College]] football team in 1944 when the coach left to serve in the war.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brownwoodnews.com/novel-about-brownwood-resident-to-hit-shelves-nationwide-this-fall/|title=Novel about Brownwood resident to hit shelves nationwide this fall|date=April 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caller.com/story/life/columnists/2018/11/07/texana-reads-1940-s-woman-took-reins-football-team-brownwood/1922993002/|title=TEXANA READS: In 1940s, woman took reins of football team in Brownwood|website=Corpus Christi Caller-Times}}</ref>\n\nLewis taught media ethics and digital media writing classes at the [[University of North Texas]].<ref name=\"auto2\" /> Lewis taught the sports writing class at the University of Texas at Arlington.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nSince 2015, Lewis has endowed the Marjorie Herrera Lewis Speakers Series at Texas Wesleyan University. Guest speakers have included retired athlete [[Daryl Johnston]] of the Dallas Cowboys and [[Foxcatcher]] author David Thomas.<ref name=\"auto4\" /><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://txwes.edu/news-and-events/all-news/advancement-and-alumni-news/new-lewis-endowed-speakers-series-to-kick-off-with-noted-author-david-thomas/|title=New Lewis Endowed Speakers Series to kickoff with noted author|first=Texas Wesleyan|last=University|website=Texas Wesleyan University}}</ref>\n\n=== Recognition ===\nOn February 10, 2018, Lewis received recognition during halftime of the [[University of Tulsa]] women\u2019s basketball game (vs. Houston) for the 32nd anniversary of [[National Girls and Women in Sports Day]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/sportsextra/tusportsextra/tu-honors-author-marjorie-lewis-for-national-girls-and-women/article_e94cee3e-a0db-5cc8-92ea-0ca147a55c21.html|title=TU honors author Marjorie Lewis for National Girls and Women in Sports Day|first=Kelly Hines Tulsa|last=World|website=Tulsa World}}</ref>\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Sports journalists]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewis, Marjorie Herrera}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Marjorie Herrera Lewis''' (born 1957) is a [[sports journalist]] best known for her 2018 novel ''[[When the Men Were Gone]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/espnw/voices/article/25088348/ode-barrier-breakers-hidden-figures-firsts-football|title=Marjorie Herrera Lewis on the legacy of Tylene Wilson|date=October 26, 2018|website=ESPN.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://footballfoundation.org/news/2017/11/9/_96.aspx|title=Marjorie Herrera Lewis Continuing Historic Season as Only Woman Assistant Coach In College Football For Texas Wesleyan Rams|website=National Football Foundation}}</ref> In 2018, the book was selected by [[Sports Illustrated]] as one of the best sports books in its year-in-review issue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/entertainment/author-credits-tu-shirt-for-prompting-historical-novel/article_5437c374-84c0-5289-a638-486a36833bc1.html|title=Author credits TU shirt for prompting historical novel|first=Kelly Hines Tulsa|last=World|website=Tulsa World}}</ref> In 2017, at age 60, Lewis coached defensive backs at [[Texas Wesleyan University]], making her the only female college football coach at any level that year.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fortworthbusiness.com/news/briefs/toughing-it-out-texas-wesleyan-female-football-coach-takes-the/article_6fb7b0c0-cfd6-11e7-a1e5-4bda2f40a533.html|title=Toughing it out: Texas Wesleyan female football coach takes the field|first=Rick Mauch FWBP|last=Correspondent|website=Fortworthbusiness.com}}</ref> In 1984, Lewis joined the [[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]] and later became the first female beat writer to cover the [[Dallas Cowboys]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldbanner.com/sports/sports-views-marjorie-herrera-lewis-is-a-pioneer-in-texas/article_629521f8-8bd6-11e9-9c55-dbc4d39e7247.html|title=Sports Views: Marjorie Herrera Lewis is a pioneer in Texas football|first=David Claybourn &#124; Herald-Banner Sports|last=Editor|website=Herald-Banner}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBorn and raised in [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]], Lewis was the second of five children. Her father is a retired dentist, and her mother is a retired accountant. In 1975, Lewis graduated from St. Michael\u2019s High School in Santa Fe, where she competed in basketball, softball, flag football, tennis, and volleyball.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.krqe.com/news/mornings/former-santa-fe-local-tastes-success-with-novel/|title=Former Santa Fe Local Tastes Success with Novel|date=October 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.assignmentmag.com/onlineonly/2018/10/31/qtvdany5zta6k59ndii2sr89nbknkp|title=AUTHOR SPOTLIGHT: Marjorie Herrera Lewis|website=ASSIGNMENT}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nLewis holds a BS from [[Arizona State University]], an MA from [[The University of Texas at Arlington]], and an MFA from [[Southern New Hampshire University]]. Lewis also has certificates from [[Southern Methodist University]] and [[Cornell University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://marjorieherreralewis.com/author|title=When The Men Were Gone|first=When The Men Were|last=Gone|website=When The Men Were Gone}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://andreasomberg.com/aslitagent/project/marjorie-herrera-lewis/|title=Marjorie Herrera Lewis &#124; Andrea Somberg: Literary Agent}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n\n== Career ==\nLewis was the sports editor for the [[Kilgore News Herald]] from 1983 to 1984.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kilgorenewsherald.com/lifestyles/former-kilgore-news-herald-sports-editor-jumps-into-literary-world/article_26099ed2-c072-11e9-8ba7-d3dd71cadfa9.html|title=Former Kilgore News Herald sports editor jumps into literary world|first=LUCAS STROUGH|last=lstrough@kilgorenewsherald.com|website=Kilgore News Herald}}</ref> In 1984, Lewis became the first woman hired as a sports writer at the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. In 1986, she became the first woman assigned to the Dallas Cowboys beat.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dmagazine.com/publications/d-magazine/2018/december/how-a-female-sportswriter-went-from-covering-to-coaching-football/|title=How a Female Sportswriter Went From Covering to Coaching Football}}</ref> Lewis started writing for [[The Dallas Morning News]] in 1989.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldbanner.com/news/lifestyles/former-sportswriter-in-greenville-may-to-discuss-her-book-on/article_5c0e929c-8195-11e9-b469-f7eb632cec9c.html|title=Former sportswriter in Greenville May 29 to discuss her book on a Texas legend: WWII-era female football coach|first=Alice Reese &#124; Herald-Banner A&E|last=Writer|website=Herald-Banner}}</ref> During her career with the Fort Worth Star-Telegram and The Dallas Morning News, Lewis covered the Dallas Cowboys, the [[Dallas Mavericks]], the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]], and the [[Davis Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://txwes.edu/academics/artsletters/undergraduate-majors/mass-communication/marjorie-herrera-lewis-endowed-speaker-series/|title=Marjorie Herrera Lewis Endowed Speaker Series - Texas Wesleyan University|website=txwes.edu}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Lewis joined the coaching staff of the Texas Wesleyan University football team in [[Fort Worth, Texas]].<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.houstonpublicmedia.org/articles/shows/houston-matters/2018/11/28/313229/how-a-texas-woman-saved-high-school-football-when-the-men-were-gone/|title=How A Texas Woman Saved High School Football \u2018When The Men Were Gone\u2019|first=Michael|last=Hagerty|date=November 28, 2018|website=Houston Public Media}}</ref><ref>https://www.star-telegram.com/sports/college/football/article100303427.html</ref>\n\nLewis is co-editor of ''SportsDay Bound'' (second edition, [[Abilene Christian University Press]], 2018), a collection of sports stories published by The Dallas Morning News.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nLewis wrote ''When the Men Were Gone'' ([[William Morrow and Company|William Morrow]], an imprint of [[HarperCollins]]), which [[Newsweek]] included on its list of Best Books of 2019 So Far.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/best-books-2019-so-far-21-fiction-nonfiction-and-poetry-picks-read-memorial-1435723|title=Best Fiction, Nonfiction and Poetry of 2019 thus far: What to read before Summer starts|first=Kelly Wynne On 5/26/19 at 12:10 AM|last=EDT|date=May 26, 2019|website=Newsweek}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snhu.edu/about-us/newsroom/2019/08/marjorie-herrera-lewis?fbclid=IwAR2rWC8Jem3eAc-CT9p8C6Ab05C2TxHNOmbVa6tn77KJvXE-sIIpHtFDVYw|title=Q&A with Sports Journalist, Novelist Marjorie Herrera Lewis '16MFA|website=www.snhu.edu}}</ref> The book was released on October 2, 2018. The historical fiction novel is based on the life of Tylene Wilson, a teacher and assistant principal in [[Brownwood, Texas]] during [[World War II]], who volunteered to coach the [[Daniel Baker College]] football team in 1944 when the coach left to serve in the war.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brownwoodnews.com/novel-about-brownwood-resident-to-hit-shelves-nationwide-this-fall/|title=Novel about Brownwood resident to hit shelves nationwide this fall|date=April 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caller.com/story/life/columnists/2018/11/07/texana-reads-1940-s-woman-took-reins-football-team-brownwood/1922993002/|title=TEXANA READS: In 1940s, woman took reins of football team in Brownwood|website=Corpus Christi Caller-Times}}</ref>\n\nLewis taught media ethics and digital media writing classes at the [[University of North Texas]].<ref name=\"auto2\" /> Lewis taught the sports writing class at the University of Texas at Arlington.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nSince 2015, Lewis has endowed the Marjorie Herrera Lewis Speakers Series at Texas Wesleyan University. Guest speakers have included retired athlete [[Daryl Johnston]] of the Dallas Cowboys and [[Foxcatcher]] author David Thomas.<ref name=\"auto4\" /><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://txwes.edu/news-and-events/all-news/advancement-and-alumni-news/new-lewis-endowed-speakers-series-to-kick-off-with-noted-author-david-thomas/|title=New Lewis Endowed Speakers Series to kickoff with noted author|first=Texas Wesleyan|last=University|website=Texas Wesleyan University}}</ref>\n\n=== Recognition ===\nOn February 10, 2018, Lewis received recognition during halftime of the [[University of Tulsa]] women\u2019s basketball game (vs. Houston) for the 32nd anniversary of [[National Girls and Women in Sports Day]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/sportsextra/tusportsextra/tu-honors-author-marjorie-lewis-for-national-girls-and-women/article_e94cee3e-a0db-5cc8-92ea-0ca147a55c21.html|title=TU honors author Marjorie Lewis for National Girls and Women in Sports Day|first=Kelly Hines Tulsa|last=World|website=Tulsa World}}</ref>\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Sports journalists]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewis, Marjorie Herrera}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Rs923", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marjorie_Herrera_Lewis"}
{"title_page": "Twelve Olympians", "text_new": "<!-- Please see talk before modifying list. -->\n[[file:Greek - Procession of Twelve Gods and Goddesses - Walters 2340.jpg|thumb|upright=1.8|Fragment of a [[Hellenistic]] [[relief sculpture|relief]] (1st century BC{{endash}}1st century AD) depicting the twelve Olympians carrying their attributes in procession; from left to right, Hestia (scepter), Hermes (winged cap and staff), Aphrodite (veiled), Ares (helmet and spear), Demeter (scepter and wheat sheaf), Hephaestus (staff), Hera (scepter), Poseidon (trident), Athena (owl and helmet), Zeus (thunderbolt and staff), Artemis (bow and quiver), Apollo (lyre), from the [[Walters Art Museum]].<ref>[[Walters Art Museum]], [http://art.thewalters.org/detail/38764 accession number 23.40].</ref>]]\n\nIn [[ancient Greek religion]] and [[Greek mythology|mythology]], the '''twelve Olympians''' are the major deities of the [[Greek mythology|Greek]] [[Pantheon (gods)|pantheon]], commonly considered to be [[Zeus]], [[Hera]], [[Poseidon]], [[Demeter]], [[Athena]], [[Apollo]], [[Artemis]], [[Ares]], [[Hephaestus]], [[Aphrodite]], [[Hermes]], and either [[Hestia]] or [[Dionysus]].<ref>Hansen, [https://books.google.com/books?id=a-NmaO-kM2UC&pg=PA250 p. 250]; Burkert, pp. 125 ff.; Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43]; Chadwick, [https://archive.org/details/mycenaeanworld00chad/page/85 p. 85]; M\u00fcller, [https://archive.org/details/ancientartandit00welcgoog/page/n439 pp. 419 ff.]; Pache, [https://books.google.com/books?id=lNV6-HsUppsC&pg=RA2-PA308 pp. 308 ff.]; Thomas, [https://books.google.com/books?id=9CUxDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT35 p. 12]; Shapiro, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7q1LDrb9btkC&pg=PT362 p. 362]; Long, [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA140 pp. 140&ndash;141]; Morford, p. 113; Hard [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA80 p. 80].</ref> They were called ''Olympians'' because, according to tradition, they resided on [[Mount Olympus]].\n\nAlthough [[Hades]] was a major ancient Greek god, and was the brother of the first generation of Olympians (Zeus, Poseidon, Hera, Demeter, and Hestia), his realm was the [[Greek underworld|underworld]], far from Olympus, and thus was not usually considered to be one of the Olympians.\n\nBesides the twelve Olympians, there were many other cultic groupings of twelve gods.\n\n==cateOlympians==\nThe Olympians were a race of [[deity|deities]], primarily consisting of a third and fourth generation of immortal beings, worshipped as the principal gods of the Greek [[pantheon (gods)|pantheon]] and so named because of their residency atop [[Mount Olympus]]. They gained their supremacy in a ten-year-long [[Titanomachy|war of gods]], in which Zeus led his siblings to victory over the previous generation of ruling gods, the [[Titan (mythology)|Titans]]. They were a family of gods, the most important consisting of the first generation of Olympians, offspring of the Titans [[Cronus]] and [[Rhea (mythology)|Rhea]]: [[Zeus]], [[Poseidon]], [[Hera]], [[Demeter]] and [[Hestia]], along with the principal offspring of Zeus: [[Athena]], [[Apollo]], [[Artemis]], [[Ares]], [[Aphrodite]],<ref>According to [[Homer]], Aphrodite was the daughter of Zeus (''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:3.374 3.374], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:20.105 20.105]; ''[[Odyssey]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-eng1:8.308 8.308], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-eng1:8.320 320]) and Dione (''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:5.370 5.370&ndash;71]), see Gantz, pp. 99&ndash;100. However, According to [[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Hes.+Th.+183 183&ndash;200], Aphrodite was born from Uranus' severed genitals, see Gantz, pp. 99&ndash;100.</ref> [[Hephaestus]], [[Hermes]], and [[Dionysus]]. Although [[Hades]] was a major deity in the Greek [[Pantheon (religion)|pantheon]], and was the brother of Zeus and the other first generation of Olympians, his realm was far away from Olympus in the [[Greek underworld|underworld]], and thus he was not usually considered to be one of the Olympians.<ref>Hansen, [https://books.google.com/books?id=a-NmaO-kM2UC&pg=PA250 p. 250]; Morford, p. 113; Hard [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA80 p. 80].</ref> Olympic gods can be contrasted to [[chthonic]] gods<ref>Chadwick, [https://archive.org/details/mycenaeanworld00chad/page/85 p. 85].</ref> including Hades, by mode of sacrifice, the latter receiving sacrifices in a ''[[bothros]]'' (\u03b2\u03cc\u03b8\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2, \"pit\") or ''[[megaron]]'' (\u03bc\u03ad\u03b3\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd, \"sunken chamber\")<ref>Dillon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=A4YyVL0sygAC&pg=PA114 p. 114].</ref> rather than at an altar.\n\nThe canonical number of Olympian gods was twelve, but besides the (thirteen) principal Olympians listed above, there were many other residents of Olympus, who thus might be considered to be Olympians.<ref>Ogden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA2, pp. 2&ndash;3]; Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43]; Hansen, [https://books.google.com/books?id=a-NmaO-kM2UC&pg=PA250 p. 250]; Burkert, p. 125.</ref> [[Heracles]] became a resident of Olympus after his [[apotheosis]] and married another Olympian resident [[Hebe (mythology)|Hebe]].<ref>[[Herodotus]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0126%3Abook%3D2%3Achapter%3D43 2.43\u201344].</ref> According to Hesiod, the children of [[Styx]]: [[Zelus]] (Envy), [[Nike (mythology)|Nike]] (Victory), [[Cratos]] (Power), and [[Bia (mythology)|Bia]] (Force), \"have no house apart from Zeus, nor any dwelling nor path except that wherein God leads them, but they dwell always with Zeus.\"<ref>[[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0020.tlg001.perseus-eng1:371-403 386&ndash;388].</ref> Some others who might be considered Olympians, include the [[Muses]], the [[Graces]], [[Iris (mythology)|Iris]], [[Dione (Titaness)|Dione]], [[Eileithyia]], the [[Horae]], and [[Ganymede (mythology)|Ganymede]].<ref>Just who might be called an Olympian is not entirely clear. For example Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43], describes Heracles, Hebe, the Muses, and the Graces as Olympians, and on [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA45 p. 45], lists Iris, Dione, and Eileithyia among the Homeric Olympians, while Hansen, [https://books.google.com/books?id=a-NmaO-kM2UC&pg=PA250 p. 250], describes Heracles, Hebe, the Horae, and Ganymede as notable residents of Olympus, but says they \"are not ordinarily classified as Olympians\".</ref>\n\n==Twelve gods==\nBesides the twelve Olympians, there were many other various cultic groupings of twelve gods throughout ancient Greece. The earliest evidence of Greek religious practice involving twelve gods ([[Ancient Greek|Greek]]: \u03b4\u03c9\u03b4\u03b5\u03ba\u03ac\u03b8\u03b5\u03bf\u03bd, ''d\u014ddek\u00e1theon'', from \u03b4\u03ce\u03b4\u03b5\u03ba\u03b1 ''d\u014ddeka'', \"twelve\" and \u03b8\u03b5\u03bf\u03af ''theoi'', \"gods\") comes no earlier than the late sixth century BC.<ref>Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43]; Rutherford, p. 43;.</ref> According to [[Thucydides]], an [[Altar of the Twelve Gods|altar of the twelve gods]] was established in the [[agora]] of [[Ancient Athens|Athens]] by the [[archon]] Pisistratus (son of [[Hippias (tyrant)|Hippias]], and the grandson of the tyrant [[Pisistratus]]), in  c. 522 BC.<ref>Rutherford, pp. 43&ndash;44; [[Thucydides]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0105%3Abook%3D6%3Achapter%3D54 6.54.6-7].</ref> The altar became the central point from which distances from Athens were measured and a place of supplication and refuge.<ref>Gadbery, p. 447.</ref>\n\n[[Olympia, Greece|Olympia]] apparently also had an early tradition of twelve gods.<ref>Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43]; Rutherford, p. 44; Long, pp. 58&ndash;62 (T 13), 154&ndash;157.</ref> The ''[[Homeric Hymns|Homeric Hymn to Hermes]]'' (c. 500 BC) has the god [[Hermes]] divide a sacrifice of two cows he has stolen from Apollo, into twelve parts, on the banks of the river [[Alfeios|Alpheius]] (presumably at Olympia):\n:\"Next glad-hearted Hermes dragged the rich meats he had prepared and put them on a smooth, flat stone, and divided them into twelve portions distributed by lot, making each portion wholly honorable.\"<ref>Long, pp. 61\u201362 (T 13 G), 156\u2013157; ''[[Homeric Hymns|Homeric Hymn to Hermes]]'', [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text;jsessionid=D804873CE4D29E774667567AC3A6A3E0?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0138%3Ahymn%3D4%3Acard%3D94 128&ndash;129].</ref>\n\nPindar, in an ode written to be sung at Olympia c. 480 BC, has [[Heracles]] sacrificing, alongside the Alpheius, to the \"twelve ruling gods\":<ref>Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43]; Rutherford, p. 44; Long, pp. 59&ndash;60 (T 13 C), 154&ndash;155.</ref>\n:\"He [Heracles] enclosed the [[Altis]] all around and marked it off in the open, and he made the encircling area a resting-place for feasting, honoring the stream of the Alpheus along with the twelve ruling gods.\"<ref>[[Pindar]], ''Olympian'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0162%3Abook%3DO.%3Apoem%3D10 10.49].</ref>\n\nAnother of Pindar's Olympian odes mentions \"six double altars\".<ref>Rutherford, p. 44; Long, pp. 58 (T 13 A), 154; [[Pindar]], ''Olympian''   [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0033.tlg001.perseus-eng1:5 5.5].</ref> [[Herodorus of Heraclea]] (c. 400 BC) also has Heracles founding a shrine at Olympia, with six pairs of gods, each pair sharing a single altar.<ref>Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43]; Rutherford, p. 47; Long, pp. 58&ndash;59 (T 13 B), 154; ''FGrH'' 31 F34a-b.</ref>\n\nMany other places had cults of the twelve gods, including [[Delos]], [[Chalcedon]], [[Magnesia on the Maeander]], and [[Leontinoi]] in [[Sicily]].<ref>Rutherford, p. 45; Delos: Long, pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA11 11], [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA87 87&ndash;90] (T 26), [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA182 182]; Chalcedon: Long, pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA56 56]&ndash;[https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA57 57] (T 11 D), [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA217 217]&ndash;[https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA218 218]; Magnesia on the Maeander: Long, [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA53 pp. 53&ndash;54] (T 7), [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA221 221]&ndash;[https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA223 223]; Leontinoi: Long, pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA95 95]&ndash;[https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA96 96] (T 32), [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA157 p. 157].</ref> As with the twelve Olympians, although the number of gods was fixed at twelve, the membership varied.<ref>Long, pp. 360&ndash;361, lists 54 Greek (and Roman) gods, including the thirteen Olympians mentioned above, who have been identified as members of one or more cultic groupings of twelve gods.</ref> While the majority of the gods included as members of these other cults of twelve gods were Olympians, non-Olympians were also sometimes included. For example, Herodorus of Heraclea identified the six pairs of gods at Olympia as: Zeus and Poseidon, Hera and Athena, Hermes and Apollo, the Graces and Dionysus, Artemis and [[Alpheus (deity)|Alpheus]], and [[Cronus]] and [[Rhea (mythology)|Rhea]].<ref>Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43]; Rutherford, p. 47; Hard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA81 p. 81]; Long, pp. 58&ndash;59 (T 13 B), 141, 154; ''FGrH'' 31 F34a-b.</ref> Thus while this list includes the eight Olympians: Zeus, Poseidon, Hera, Athena, Hermes, Apollo, Artemis, and Dionysus, it also contains three clear non-Olympians: the Titan parents of the first generation of Olympians, Cronus and Rhea, and the river god Alpheius, with the status of the Graces (here apparently counted as one god) being unclear.\n\n[[Plato]] connected \"twelve gods\" with the twelve months, and implies that he considered [[Pluto (mythology)#In Greek literature and philosophy|Pluto]] one of the twelve in proposing that the final month be devoted to him and the spirits of the dead.<ref>Rutherford, pp. 45&ndash;46; [[Plato]], ''[[Laws (Plato)|The Laws]]'' 828 [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0166%3Abook%3D8%3Asection%3D828b b-d]</ref>\n\nThe Roman poet [[Ennius]] gives the [[interpretatio graeca|Roman equivalents]] (the ''[[Dii Consentes]]'') as six male-female complements,<ref name=\"PapAm\">{{cite encyclopedia|title=Greek mythology|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia Americana|year=1993|volume=13|page=431}}</ref> preserving the place of [[Vesta (mythology)|Vesta]] (Greek Hestia), who played a crucial role in [[Religion in ancient Rome|Roman religion]] as a state goddess maintained by the [[Vestals]].\n\n==List==\nThere is no single canonical list of the twelve Olympian gods. The thirteen gods and goddesses most commonly considered to be one of the twelve Olympians are listed below.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"padding:0.5em 0.5em;white-space:nowrap;\"|Greek!! style=\"padding:0.5em 0.5em;white-space:nowrap;\" |Roman!! style=\"padding:0.5em 0.5em;white-space:nowrap;\" |Image!!style=\"padding:0.5em 0.5em;white-space:nowrap;\"|Functions and attributes\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Zeus]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Jupiter (mythology)|Jupiter]] || [[File:Jupiter Smyrna Louvre Ma13.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |King of the gods and ruler of [[Mount Olympus]]; god of the sky, lightning, thunder, law, order and justice. <br/> The youngest child of the Titans Cronus and Rhea. Brother and husband of Hera, although he had many lovers, also brother of Poseidon, Hades, Demeter, and Hestia. <br/> His symbols include the thunderbolt, eagle, oak tree, bull, scepter, and scales. \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Hera]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Juno (mythology)|Juno]] || [[File:Hera Campana Louvre Ma2283.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Queen of the gods and the goddess of marriage, women, childbirth and family. <br/> The youngest daughter of Cronus and Rhea. Sister and wife of Zeus. Being the goddess of marriage, she frequently tried to get revenge on Zeus' lovers and their children. <br/> Her symbols include the peacock, cuckoo, and cow. \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Poseidon]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Neptune (mythology)|Neptune]] || [[File:0036MAN Poseidon.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |God of the seas, water, storms, hurricanes, earthquakes and horses. <br/> The middle son of Cronus and Rhea. Brother of Zeus and Hades. Married to the [[Nereid]] [[Amphitrite]]; although, as with many of the male Greek gods, he had many lovers. <br/> His symbols include the horse, bull, dolphin, and trident.  \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Demeter]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Ceres (mythology)|Ceres]] || [[File:Demeter Altemps Inv8546.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Goddess of the harvest, fertility, agriculture, nature and the seasons. She presided over [[grains]] and the [[fertility]] of the earth. <br/> The middle daughter of Cronus and Rhea. Also the lover of Zeus and Poseidon, and the mother of [[Persephone]]. <br/> Her symbols include the poppy, wheat, torch, cornucopia, and pig.  \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Athena]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Minerva]] || [[File:Mattei Athena Louvre Ma530 n2.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Goddess of wisdom, handicraft, and warfare.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Inc |first1=Merriam-Webster |title=Merriam-Webster's Encyclopedia of Literature |date=1995 |publisher=Merriam-Webster |isbn=9780877790426 |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=eKNK1YwHcQ4C&pg=PA81url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eKNK1YwHcQ4C&pg=PA81 81]}}</ref> <br/> The daughter of Zeus and the [[Oceanid]] [[Metis (mythology)|Metis]], she rose from her father's head fully grown and in full battle armor. <br/> Her symbols include the owl and the olive tree.  \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Apollo]] / <br/>Apollon || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Apollo]]|| [[File:Apollo of the Belvedere.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |God of light, the sun, [[Oracle|prophecy]], [[philosophy]], archery, truth, inspiration, poetry, music, arts, manly beauty, medicine, healing, and plague. <br/> The son of Zeus and [[Leto]], and the twin brother of Artemis. <br/> His symbols include the sun, bow and arrow, lyre, swan, and mouse.  \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Artemis]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Diana (mythology)|Diana]] || [[File:Diane de Versailles Leochares.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Goddess of the hunt, the wilderness, virginity, the moon, archery, childbirth, protection and plague. <br/> The daughter of Zeus and [[Leto]], and the twin sister of Apollo. <br/> Her symbols include the moon, horse, deer, hound, she-bear, snake, cypress tree, and bow and arrow.  \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Ares]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Mars (mythology)|Mars]] || [[File:Ares Canope Villa Adriana b.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |God of war, violence, bloodshed and manly virtues. <br/> The son of Zeus and Hera, all the other gods despised him except Aphrodite. His Latin name, Mars, gave us the word \"[[wiktionary:martial|martial]].\" <br/> His symbols include the boar, serpent, dog, vulture, spear, and shield. \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Aphrodite]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Venus (mythology)|Venus]] || [[File:NAMA Aphrodite Syracuse.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Goddess of love, pleasure, passion, procreation, fertility, beauty and desire. <br/> The daughter of Zeus and the Oceanid Dione, or perhaps born from the sea foam after [[Uranus (mythology)|Uranus]]' blood dripped into the sea after being castrated by his youngest son, [[Cronus]], who then threw his father's genitals into the sea. Married to Hephaestus, although she had many adulterous affairs, most notably with Ares. Her name gave us the word \"[[aphrodisiac]]\", while her Latin name, Venus, gave us the word \"[[venereal]]\". <br/> Her symbols include the dove, bird, apple, bee, swan, [[myrtus|myrtle]], and rose. \n|- \n| style=\"padding-left:0.65em;\"|[[Hephaestus]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Vulcan (mythology)|Vulcan]] || [[File:Vulcan Coustou Louvre MR1814.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Master blacksmith and craftsman of the gods; god of the forge, craftsmanship, invention, fire and volcanoes. <br/> The son of Hera, either by Zeus or through [[parthenogenesis]]. Married to Aphrodite. His Latin name, Vulcan, gave us the word \"[[volcano]].\" <br/> His symbols include fire, anvil, axe, donkey, hammer, tongs, and quail.  \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Hermes]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Mercury (mythology)|Mercury]] || [[File:Hermes Ingenui Pio-Clementino Inv544.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Messenger of the gods; god of travel, commerce, communication, borders, eloquence, diplomacy, thieves and games. He was also the guide of dead souls. <br/> The son of Zeus and the nymph [[Maia]]. The second-youngest Olympian, just older than Dionysus. <br/> His symbols include the [[caduceus]] (staff entwined with two snakes), winged sandals and cap, stork, and tortoise (whose shell he used to invent the lyre).  \n|-\n|colspan=4 align=center|''Most lists of the \"twelve Olympians\" consist of the above eleven plus either Hestia or Dionysus''\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Hestia]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Vesta (mythology)|Vesta]] || [[File:Hestia Giustiniani.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Goddess of the hearth, fire and of the right ordering of domesticity and the family; she was born into the first Olympian generation and was one of the original twelve Olympians. <br/> She is the first child of Cronus and Rhea, the elder sister of Hades, Demeter, Poseidon, Hera, and Zeus. \n<br/> ''Some lists of the Twelve Olympians omit her in favor of Dionysus, but the speculation that she gave her throne to him in order to keep the peace seems to be modern invention.'' \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Dionysus]] / <br/>[[Bacchus]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"| [[Bacchus]] || [[File:Dionysos Louvre Ma87 n2.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |God of wine, the grape vine, fertility, festivity, ecstasy, madness and resurrection. Patron god of the art of [[theatre]]. <br/> The son of Zeus and the mortal Theban princess [[Semele]]. Married to the Cretan princess [[Ariadne]]. The youngest Olympian god, as well as the only one to have a mortal mother. <br/> His symbols include the grapevine, ivy, cup, tiger, panther, leopard, dolphin, goat, and pinecone.  \n|}\n\n==Genealogy==\n{{chart top|Major Olympians' family tree&nbsp;<ref>This chart is based upon [[Hesiod]]'s ''[[Theogony]]'', unless otherwise noted.</ref>|collapsed=no}}\n{{chart/start}}\n{{chart|}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | |URA |y|GAI |URA=[[Uranus (mythology)|Uranus]]|GAI=[[Gaia (mythology)|Gaia]]}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | |,|-|^|-|.}}\n{{chart|URA| | | | | | | | |CRO |y|RHE |URA=<small>Uranus' genitals</small>|CRO=[[Cronus]]|RHE=[[Rhea (mythology)|Rhea]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|^|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.}}\n{{chart| |!| |ZEU |V|~|~|y|~|HER | |POS | |HAD | |DEM | |HES |ZEU=[[Zeus|'''ZEUS''']]|HER=[[Hera|'''HERA''']]|POS=[[Poseidon|'''POSEIDON''']]|HAD=[[Hades]]|DEM=[[Demeter|'''DEMETER''']]|HES=[[Hestia|'''HESTIA''']]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| |,|^|-|.| |!}}\n{{chart|border=0| |!| | | | |:| |!| |AAA |!|AAA= &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;a <ref>According to [[Homer]], ''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:1.570 1.570&ndash;579],  [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:14.338 14.338], ''[[Odyssey]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-eng1:8.312 8.312], Hephaestus was apparently the son of Hera and Zeus, see Gantz, p. 74.</ref>}}\n{{chart|border=0| |!| | | | |:| |!| | |!|BBB |BBB=&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;b <ref>According to [[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Hes.+Th.+927 927&ndash;929], Hephaestus was produced by Hera alone, with no father, see Gantz, p. 74.</ref>}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| |!| | |!| |!}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:|ARE | |HEP |HEP=[[Hephaestus|'''HEPHAESTUS''']]|ARE=[[Ares|'''ARES''']]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |D|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|~|MET |MET=[[Metis (mythology)|Metis]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| | |ATH |ATH=[[Athena|'''ATHENA''']] <ref>According to [[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Hes.+Th.+886 886&ndash;890], of Zeus' children by his seven wives, Athena was the first to be conceived, but the last to be born; Zeus impregnated Metis then swallowed her, later Zeus himself gave birth to Athena \"from his head\", see Gantz, pp. 51&ndash;52, 83&ndash;84.</ref>}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |D|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|~|LET |LET=[[Leto]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| |,|-|^|-|.}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:|APO | |ART |APO=[[Apollo|'''APOLLO''']]|ART=[[Artemis|'''ARTEMIS''']]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |D|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|~|MAI |MAI=[[Maia (mythology)|Maia]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| | |HER |HER=[[Hermes|'''HERMES''']]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |D|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|~|SEM |SEM=[[Semele]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| | |DIO |DIO=[[Dionysus|'''DIONYSUS''']]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |L|~|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|DIO |DIO=[[Dione (Titaness)|Dione]]}}\n{{chart|border=0|AAA | | | | | | | |BBB|AAA=&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;a <ref>According to [[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Hes.+Th.+183 183&ndash;200], Aphrodite was born from Uranus' severed genitals, see Gantz, pp. 99&ndash;100.</ref>|BBB=&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;b <ref>According to [[Homer]], Aphrodite was the daughter of Zeus (''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:3.374 3.374], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:20.105 20.105]; ''[[Odyssey]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-eng1:8.308 8.308], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-eng1:8.320 320]) and Dione (''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:5.370 5.370&ndash;71]), see Gantz, pp. 99&ndash;100.</ref>}}\n{{chart| |`|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|.| |!}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | |APH |APH=[[Aphrodite|'''APHRODITE''']]}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ancient Greece|Religion}}\n\n* [[Dii Consentes]], the Roman equivalent of the twelve Olympians\n* [[Family tree of the Greek gods]]\n* ''[[Interpretatio graeca]]'', including a table of mythological equivalents\n* [[List of Greek mythological characters]]\n* [[Supreme Council of Ethnikoi Hellenes]]\n* [[Hellenismos]]\n* [[Olympia, Greece|Olympia]]\n* [[Olympians (Marvel Comics)]]\n* [[Olympian Gods (DC Comics)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* [[Walter Burkert|Burkert, Walter]], ''Greek Religion'', [[Harvard University Press]], 1985. {{ISBN|0-674-36281-0}}.\n* Chadwick, John, ''The Mycenaean World'', Cambridge University Press, 1976. {{ISBN|9780521290371}}.\n* Dillon, Matthew, ''Girls and Women in Classical Greek Religion''. London: Routledge. (2002). {{ISBN|0415202728}}.\n* Dowden, Ken, \"Olympian Gods, Olympian Pantheon\", in ''A Companion to Greek Religion'', Daniel Ogden editor, John Wiley & Sons, 2010. {{ISBN|9781444334173}}.\n* Gadbery, Laura M., \"The Sanctuary of the Twelve Gods in the Athenian Agora: A Revised View\", ''Hesperia'' '''61''' (1992), pp.&nbsp;447&ndash;489.\n* Gantz, Timothy, ''Early Greek Myth: A Guide to Literary and Artistic Sources'', Johns Hopkins University Press, 1996, Two volumes: {{ISBN|978-0-8018-5360-9}} (Vol. 1), {{ISBN|978-0-8018-5362-3}} (Vol. 2).\n*[[William Hansen (classicist)|Hansen, William]], William F. Hansen, ''Classical Mythology: A Guide to the Mythical World of the Greeks and Romans'', Oxford University Press, 2005. {{ISBN|9780195300352}}.\n* Hard, Robin, ''The Routledge Handbook of Greek Mythology: Based on H.J. Rose's \"Handbook of Greek Mythology\"'', Psychology Press, 2004, {{ISBN|9780415186360}}. [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false Google Books].\n* [[Herodotus]]; [[The Histories of Herodotus|''Histories'']], [[A. D. Godley]] (translator), Cambridge: Harvard University Press, 1920; {{ISBN|0674991338}}. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Hdt.+1.1.0 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n* [[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'', in ''The Homeric Hymns and Homerica with an English Translation by Hugh G. Evelyn-White'', Cambridge, Massachusetts., Harvard University Press; London, William Heinemann Ltd. 1914. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0130%3Acard%3D1 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n* [[Homer]], ''The Iliad with an English Translation by A.T. Murray, Ph.D. in two volumes''. Cambridge, Massachusetts., Harvard University Press; London, William Heinemann, Ltd. 1924. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0134%3Abook%3D1%3Acard%3D1 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n* [[Homer]]; ''The Odyssey with an English Translation by A.T. Murray, PH.D. in two volumes''. Cambridge, Massachusetts., Harvard University Press; London, William Heinemann, Ltd. 1919. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0136%3Abook%3D1%3Acard%3D1 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n* [[Homeric Hymns|''Homeric Hymn to Hermes (4)'']], in ''The Homeric Hymns and Homerica with an English Translation by Hugh G. Evelyn-White'', Cambridge, Massachusetts., Harvard University Press; London, William Heinemann Ltd. 1914. [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0013.tlg004.perseus-eng1:1-29 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n* Long, Charlotte R., ''The Twelve Gods of Greece and Rome'', Brill Archive, Jan 1, 1987. [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&source=gbs_navlinks_s Google Books]\n* Morford, Mark P. O., Robert J. Lenardon, ''Classical Mythology'', Eighth Edition, Oxford University Press, 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-19-530805-1}}.\n* M\u00fcller, Karl Otfried, ''Ancient Art and Its Remains: Or, A Manual of the Archaeology of Art'', translated by John Leitch, B. Quaritch, 1852.\n* Ogden, Daniel \"Introduction\" to ''A Companion to Greek Religion'', Daniel Ogden editor, John Wiley & Sons, 2010. {{ISBN|9781444334173}}.\n* Pache, Corinne Ondine, \"Gods, Greek\" in ''The Oxford Encyclopedia of Ancient Greece and Rome, Volume 3'', Oxford University Press. 2010. {{ISBN|9780195170726}}.\n* [[Pindar]], ''Odes'', Diane Arnson Svarlien. 1990.\n* [[Plato]], ''[[Laws (dialogue)|Laws]]'' in ''Plato in Twelve Volumes'', Vols. 10 & 11 translated by R.G. Bury. Cambridge, Massachusetts, [[Harvard University Press]]; London, William Heinemann Ltd. 1967 & 1968. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0059.tlg034.perseus-eng1  Online version at the Perseus Digital Library]\n* Rutherford, Ian, \"Canonizing the Pantheon: the Dodekatheon in Greek Religion and its Origins\" in ''The Gods of Ancient Greece: Identities and Transformations'', editors Jan N. Bremmer, Andrew Erskine, Edinburgh University Press 2010. {{ISBN|978-0748637980}}. [http://site.ebrary.com/lib/bostonuniv/reader.action?docID=10409250 Online version]\n* Shapiro, H. A., \"Chapter 20: Olympian Gods at Home and Abroad\" in ''A Companion to Greek Art'', editors Tyler Jo Smith, Dimitris Plantzos, John Wiley & Sons, 2012. {{ISBN|9781118273371}}.\n* Thomas, Edmund, \"From the pantheon of the gods to the Pantheon of Rome\" in ''Pantheons: Transformations of a Monumental Idea'', editors Richard Wrigley, [[Matthew Craske]], Ashgate Publishing, Ltd., 2004. {{ISBN|9780754608080}}.\n* [[Thucydides]], ''Thucydides translated into English; with introduction, marginal analysis, notes, and indices. Volume 1.'', Benjamin Jowett. translator. Oxford. Clarendon Press. 1881. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3atext%3a1999.04.0105 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n\n{{Greek religion}}\n{{Greek mythology (deities)}}\n{{Greek myth (Olympian)}}\n\n[[Category:Twelve Olympians| ]]\n[[Category:Cultural lists|Twelve Olympians]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please see talk before modifying list. -->\n[[file:Greek - Procession of Twelve Gods and Goddesses - Walters 2340.jpg|thumb|upright=1.8|Fragment of a [[Hellenistic]] [[relief sculpture|relief]] (1st century BC{{endash}}1st century AD) depicting the twelve Olympians carrying their attributes in procession; from left to right, Hestia (scepter), Hermes (winged cap and staff), Aphrodite (veiled), Ares (helmet and spear), Demeter (scepter and wheat sheaf), Hephaestus (staff), Hera (scepter), Poseidon (trident), Athena (owl and helmet), Zeus (thunderbolt and staff), Artemis (bow and quiver), Apollo (lyre), from the [[Walters Art Museum]].<ref>[[Walters Art Museum]], [http://art.thewalters.org/detail/38764 accession number 23.40].</ref>]]\n\nIn [[ancient Greek religion]] and [[Greek mythology|mythology]], the '''twelve Olympians''' are the major deities of the [[Greek mythology|Greek]] [[Pantheon (gods)|pantheon]], commonly considered to be [[Zeus]], [[Hera]], [[Poseidon]], [[Demeter]], [[Athena]], [[Apollo]], [[Artemis]], [[Ares]], [[Hephaestus]], [[Aphrodite]], [[Hermes]], and either [[Hestia]] or [[Dionysus]].<ref>Hansen, [https://books.google.com/books?id=a-NmaO-kM2UC&pg=PA250 p. 250]; Burkert, pp. 125 ff.; Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43]; Chadwick, [https://archive.org/details/mycenaeanworld00chad/page/85 p. 85]; M\u00fcller, [https://archive.org/details/ancientartandit00welcgoog/page/n439 pp. 419 ff.]; Pache, [https://books.google.com/books?id=lNV6-HsUppsC&pg=RA2-PA308 pp. 308 ff.]; Thomas, [https://books.google.com/books?id=9CUxDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT35 p. 12]; Shapiro, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7q1LDrb9btkC&pg=PT362 p. 362]; Long, [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA140 pp. 140&ndash;141]; Morford, p. 113; Hard [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA80 p. 80].</ref> They were called ''Olympians'' because, according to tradition, they resided on [[Mount Olympus]].\n\nAlthough [[Hades]] was a major ancient Greek god, and was the brother of the first generation of Olympians (Zeus, Poseidon, Hera, Demeter, and Hestia), his realm was the [[Greek underworld|underworld]], far from Olympus, and thus was not usually considered to be one of the Olympians.\n\nBesides the twelve Olympians, there were many other cultic groupings of twelve gods.\n\n==Olympians==\nThe Olympians were a race of [[deity|deities]], primarily consisting of a third and fourth generation of immortal beings, worshipped as the principal gods of the Greek [[pantheon (gods)|pantheon]] and so named because of their residency atop [[Mount Olympus]]. They gained their supremacy in a ten-year-long [[Titanomachy|war of gods]], in which Zeus led his siblings to victory over the previous generation of ruling gods, the [[Titan (mythology)|Titans]]. They were a family of gods, the most important consisting of the first generation of Olympians, offspring of the Titans [[Cronus]] and [[Rhea (mythology)|Rhea]]: [[Zeus]], [[Poseidon]], [[Hera]], [[Demeter]] and [[Hestia]], along with the principal offspring of Zeus: [[Athena]], [[Apollo]], [[Artemis]], [[Ares]], [[Aphrodite]],<ref>According to [[Homer]], Aphrodite was the daughter of Zeus (''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:3.374 3.374], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:20.105 20.105]; ''[[Odyssey]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-eng1:8.308 8.308], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-eng1:8.320 320]) and Dione (''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:5.370 5.370&ndash;71]), see Gantz, pp. 99&ndash;100. However, According to [[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Hes.+Th.+183 183&ndash;200], Aphrodite was born from Uranus' severed genitals, see Gantz, pp. 99&ndash;100.</ref> [[Hephaestus]], [[Hermes]], and [[Dionysus]]. Although [[Hades]] was a major deity in the Greek [[Pantheon (religion)|pantheon]], and was the brother of Zeus and the other first generation of Olympians, his realm was far away from Olympus in the [[Greek underworld|underworld]], and thus he was not usually considered to be one of the Olympians.<ref>Hansen, [https://books.google.com/books?id=a-NmaO-kM2UC&pg=PA250 p. 250]; Morford, p. 113; Hard [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA80 p. 80].</ref> Olympic gods can be contrasted to [[chthonic]] gods<ref>Chadwick, [https://archive.org/details/mycenaeanworld00chad/page/85 p. 85].</ref> including Hades, by mode of sacrifice, the latter receiving sacrifices in a ''[[bothros]]'' (\u03b2\u03cc\u03b8\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2, \"pit\") or ''[[megaron]]'' (\u03bc\u03ad\u03b3\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd, \"sunken chamber\")<ref>Dillon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=A4YyVL0sygAC&pg=PA114 p. 114].</ref> rather than at an altar.\n\nThe canonical number of Olympian gods was twelve, but besides the (thirteen) principal Olympians listed above, there were many other residents of Olympus, who thus might be considered to be Olympians.<ref>Ogden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA2, pp. 2&ndash;3]; Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43]; Hansen, [https://books.google.com/books?id=a-NmaO-kM2UC&pg=PA250 p. 250]; Burkert, p. 125.</ref> [[Heracles]] became a resident of Olympus after his [[apotheosis]] and married another Olympian resident [[Hebe (mythology)|Hebe]].<ref>[[Herodotus]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0126%3Abook%3D2%3Achapter%3D43 2.43\u201344].</ref> According to Hesiod, the children of [[Styx]]: [[Zelus]] (Envy), [[Nike (mythology)|Nike]] (Victory), [[Cratos]] (Power), and [[Bia (mythology)|Bia]] (Force), \"have no house apart from Zeus, nor any dwelling nor path except that wherein God leads them, but they dwell always with Zeus.\"<ref>[[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0020.tlg001.perseus-eng1:371-403 386&ndash;388].</ref> Some others who might be considered Olympians, include the [[Muses]], the [[Graces]], [[Iris (mythology)|Iris]], [[Dione (Titaness)|Dione]], [[Eileithyia]], the [[Horae]], and [[Ganymede (mythology)|Ganymede]].<ref>Just who might be called an Olympian is not entirely clear. For example Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43], describes Heracles, Hebe, the Muses, and the Graces as Olympians, and on [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA45 p. 45], lists Iris, Dione, and Eileithyia among the Homeric Olympians, while Hansen, [https://books.google.com/books?id=a-NmaO-kM2UC&pg=PA250 p. 250], describes Heracles, Hebe, the Horae, and Ganymede as notable residents of Olympus, but says they \"are not ordinarily classified as Olympians\".</ref>\n\n==Twelve gods==\nBesides the twelve Olympians, there were many other various cultic groupings of twelve gods throughout ancient Greece. The earliest evidence of Greek religious practice involving twelve gods ([[Ancient Greek|Greek]]: \u03b4\u03c9\u03b4\u03b5\u03ba\u03ac\u03b8\u03b5\u03bf\u03bd, ''d\u014ddek\u00e1theon'', from \u03b4\u03ce\u03b4\u03b5\u03ba\u03b1 ''d\u014ddeka'', \"twelve\" and \u03b8\u03b5\u03bf\u03af ''theoi'', \"gods\") comes no earlier than the late sixth century BC.<ref>Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43]; Rutherford, p. 43;.</ref> According to [[Thucydides]], an [[Altar of the Twelve Gods|altar of the twelve gods]] was established in the [[agora]] of [[Ancient Athens|Athens]] by the [[archon]] Pisistratus (son of [[Hippias (tyrant)|Hippias]], and the grandson of the tyrant [[Pisistratus]]), in  c. 522 BC.<ref>Rutherford, pp. 43&ndash;44; [[Thucydides]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0105%3Abook%3D6%3Achapter%3D54 6.54.6-7].</ref> The altar became the central point from which distances from Athens were measured and a place of supplication and refuge.<ref>Gadbery, p. 447.</ref>\n\n[[Olympia, Greece|Olympia]] apparently also had an early tradition of twelve gods.<ref>Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43]; Rutherford, p. 44; Long, pp. 58&ndash;62 (T 13), 154&ndash;157.</ref> The ''[[Homeric Hymns|Homeric Hymn to Hermes]]'' (c. 500 BC) has the god [[Hermes]] divide a sacrifice of two cows he has stolen from Apollo, into twelve parts, on the banks of the river [[Alfeios|Alpheius]] (presumably at Olympia):\n:\"Next glad-hearted Hermes dragged the rich meats he had prepared and put them on a smooth, flat stone, and divided them into twelve portions distributed by lot, making each portion wholly honorable.\"<ref>Long, pp. 61\u201362 (T 13 G), 156\u2013157; ''[[Homeric Hymns|Homeric Hymn to Hermes]]'', [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text;jsessionid=D804873CE4D29E774667567AC3A6A3E0?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0138%3Ahymn%3D4%3Acard%3D94 128&ndash;129].</ref>\n\nPindar, in an ode written to be sung at Olympia c. 480 BC, has [[Heracles]] sacrificing, alongside the Alpheius, to the \"twelve ruling gods\":<ref>Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43]; Rutherford, p. 44; Long, pp. 59&ndash;60 (T 13 C), 154&ndash;155.</ref>\n:\"He [Heracles] enclosed the [[Altis]] all around and marked it off in the open, and he made the encircling area a resting-place for feasting, honoring the stream of the Alpheus along with the twelve ruling gods.\"<ref>[[Pindar]], ''Olympian'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0162%3Abook%3DO.%3Apoem%3D10 10.49].</ref>\n\nAnother of Pindar's Olympian odes mentions \"six double altars\".<ref>Rutherford, p. 44; Long, pp. 58 (T 13 A), 154; [[Pindar]], ''Olympian''   [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0033.tlg001.perseus-eng1:5 5.5].</ref> [[Herodorus of Heraclea]] (c. 400 BC) also has Heracles founding a shrine at Olympia, with six pairs of gods, each pair sharing a single altar.<ref>Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43]; Rutherford, p. 47; Long, pp. 58&ndash;59 (T 13 B), 154; ''FGrH'' 31 F34a-b.</ref>\n\nMany other places had cults of the twelve gods, including [[Delos]], [[Chalcedon]], [[Magnesia on the Maeander]], and [[Leontinoi]] in [[Sicily]].<ref>Rutherford, p. 45; Delos: Long, pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA11 11], [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA87 87&ndash;90] (T 26), [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA182 182]; Chalcedon: Long, pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA56 56]&ndash;[https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA57 57] (T 11 D), [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA217 217]&ndash;[https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA218 218]; Magnesia on the Maeander: Long, [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA53 pp. 53&ndash;54] (T 7), [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA221 221]&ndash;[https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA223 223]; Leontinoi: Long, pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA95 95]&ndash;[https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA96 96] (T 32), [https://books.google.com/books?id=3dUUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA157 p. 157].</ref> As with the twelve Olympians, although the number of gods was fixed at twelve, the membership varied.<ref>Long, pp. 360&ndash;361, lists 54 Greek (and Roman) gods, including the thirteen Olympians mentioned above, who have been identified as members of one or more cultic groupings of twelve gods.</ref> While the majority of the gods included as members of these other cults of twelve gods were Olympians, non-Olympians were also sometimes included. For example, Herodorus of Heraclea identified the six pairs of gods at Olympia as: Zeus and Poseidon, Hera and Athena, Hermes and Apollo, the Graces and Dionysus, Artemis and [[Alpheus (deity)|Alpheus]], and [[Cronus]] and [[Rhea (mythology)|Rhea]].<ref>Dowden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=yOQtHNJJU9UC&pg=PA43 p. 43]; Rutherford, p. 47; Hard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA81 p. 81]; Long, pp. 58&ndash;59 (T 13 B), 141, 154; ''FGrH'' 31 F34a-b.</ref> Thus while this list includes the eight Olympians: Zeus, Poseidon, Hera, Athena, Hermes, Apollo, Artemis, and Dionysus, it also contains three clear non-Olympians: the Titan parents of the first generation of Olympians, Cronus and Rhea, and the river god Alpheius, with the status of the Graces (here apparently counted as one god) being unclear.\n\n[[Plato]] connected \"twelve gods\" with the twelve months, and implies that he considered [[Pluto (mythology)#In Greek literature and philosophy|Pluto]] one of the twelve in proposing that the final month be devoted to him and the spirits of the dead.<ref>Rutherford, pp. 45&ndash;46; [[Plato]], ''[[Laws (Plato)|The Laws]]'' 828 [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0166%3Abook%3D8%3Asection%3D828b b-d]</ref>\n\nThe Roman poet [[Ennius]] gives the [[interpretatio graeca|Roman equivalents]] (the ''[[Dii Consentes]]'') as six male-female complements,<ref name=\"PapAm\">{{cite encyclopedia|title=Greek mythology|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia Americana|year=1993|volume=13|page=431}}</ref> preserving the place of [[Vesta (mythology)|Vesta]] (Greek Hestia), who played a crucial role in [[Religion in ancient Rome|Roman religion]] as a state goddess maintained by the [[Vestals]].\n\n==List==\nThere is no single canonical list of the twelve Olympian gods. The thirteen gods and goddesses most commonly considered to be one of the twelve Olympians are listed below.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"padding:0.5em 0.5em;white-space:nowrap;\"|Greek!! style=\"padding:0.5em 0.5em;white-space:nowrap;\" |Roman!! style=\"padding:0.5em 0.5em;white-space:nowrap;\" |Image!!style=\"padding:0.5em 0.5em;white-space:nowrap;\"|Functions and attributes\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Zeus]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Jupiter (mythology)|Jupiter]] || [[File:Jupiter Smyrna Louvre Ma13.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |King of the gods and ruler of [[Mount Olympus]]; god of the sky, lightning, thunder, law, order and justice. <br/> The youngest child of the Titans Cronus and Rhea. Brother and husband of Hera, although he had many lovers, also brother of Poseidon, Hades, Demeter, and Hestia. <br/> His symbols include the thunderbolt, eagle, oak tree, bull, scepter, and scales. \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Hera]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Juno (mythology)|Juno]] || [[File:Hera Campana Louvre Ma2283.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Queen of the gods and the goddess of marriage, women, childbirth and family. <br/> The youngest daughter of Cronus and Rhea. Sister and wife of Zeus. Being the goddess of marriage, she frequently tried to get revenge on Zeus' lovers and their children. <br/> Her symbols include the peacock, cuckoo, and cow. \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Poseidon]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Neptune (mythology)|Neptune]] || [[File:0036MAN Poseidon.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |God of the seas, water, storms, hurricanes, earthquakes and horses. <br/> The middle son of Cronus and Rhea. Brother of Zeus and Hades. Married to the [[Nereid]] [[Amphitrite]]; although, as with many of the male Greek gods, he had many lovers. <br/> His symbols include the horse, bull, dolphin, and trident.  \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Demeter]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Ceres (mythology)|Ceres]] || [[File:Demeter Altemps Inv8546.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Goddess of the harvest, fertility, agriculture, nature and the seasons. She presided over [[grains]] and the [[fertility]] of the earth. <br/> The middle daughter of Cronus and Rhea. Also the lover of Zeus and Poseidon, and the mother of [[Persephone]]. <br/> Her symbols include the poppy, wheat, torch, cornucopia, and pig.  \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Athena]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Minerva]] || [[File:Mattei Athena Louvre Ma530 n2.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Goddess of wisdom, handicraft, and warfare.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Inc |first1=Merriam-Webster |title=Merriam-Webster's Encyclopedia of Literature |date=1995 |publisher=Merriam-Webster |isbn=9780877790426 |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=eKNK1YwHcQ4C&pg=PA81url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eKNK1YwHcQ4C&pg=PA81 81]}}</ref> <br/> The daughter of Zeus and the [[Oceanid]] [[Metis (mythology)|Metis]], she rose from her father's head fully grown and in full battle armor. <br/> Her symbols include the owl and the olive tree.  \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Apollo]] / <br/>Apollon || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Apollo]]|| [[File:Apollo of the Belvedere.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |God of light, the sun, [[Oracle|prophecy]], [[philosophy]], archery, truth, inspiration, poetry, music, arts, manly beauty, medicine, healing, and plague. <br/> The son of Zeus and [[Leto]], and the twin brother of Artemis. <br/> His symbols include the sun, bow and arrow, lyre, swan, and mouse.  \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Artemis]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Diana (mythology)|Diana]] || [[File:Diane de Versailles Leochares.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Goddess of the hunt, the wilderness, virginity, the moon, archery, childbirth, protection and plague. <br/> The daughter of Zeus and [[Leto]], and the twin sister of Apollo. <br/> Her symbols include the moon, horse, deer, hound, she-bear, snake, cypress tree, and bow and arrow.  \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Ares]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Mars (mythology)|Mars]] || [[File:Ares Canope Villa Adriana b.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |God of war, violence, bloodshed and manly virtues. <br/> The son of Zeus and Hera, all the other gods despised him except Aphrodite. His Latin name, Mars, gave us the word \"[[wiktionary:martial|martial]].\" <br/> His symbols include the boar, serpent, dog, vulture, spear, and shield. \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Aphrodite]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Venus (mythology)|Venus]] || [[File:NAMA Aphrodite Syracuse.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Goddess of love, pleasure, passion, procreation, fertility, beauty and desire. <br/> The daughter of Zeus and the Oceanid Dione, or perhaps born from the sea foam after [[Uranus (mythology)|Uranus]]' blood dripped into the sea after being castrated by his youngest son, [[Cronus]], who then threw his father's genitals into the sea. Married to Hephaestus, although she had many adulterous affairs, most notably with Ares. Her name gave us the word \"[[aphrodisiac]]\", while her Latin name, Venus, gave us the word \"[[venereal]]\". <br/> Her symbols include the dove, bird, apple, bee, swan, [[myrtus|myrtle]], and rose. \n|- \n| style=\"padding-left:0.65em;\"|[[Hephaestus]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Vulcan (mythology)|Vulcan]] || [[File:Vulcan Coustou Louvre MR1814.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Master blacksmith and craftsman of the gods; god of the forge, craftsmanship, invention, fire and volcanoes. <br/> The son of Hera, either by Zeus or through [[parthenogenesis]]. Married to Aphrodite. His Latin name, Vulcan, gave us the word \"[[volcano]].\" <br/> His symbols include fire, anvil, axe, donkey, hammer, tongs, and quail.  \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Hermes]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Mercury (mythology)|Mercury]] || [[File:Hermes Ingenui Pio-Clementino Inv544.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Messenger of the gods; god of travel, commerce, communication, borders, eloquence, diplomacy, thieves and games. He was also the guide of dead souls. <br/> The son of Zeus and the nymph [[Maia]]. The second-youngest Olympian, just older than Dionysus. <br/> His symbols include the [[caduceus]] (staff entwined with two snakes), winged sandals and cap, stork, and tortoise (whose shell he used to invent the lyre).  \n|-\n|colspan=4 align=center|''Most lists of the \"twelve Olympians\" consist of the above eleven plus either Hestia or Dionysus''\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Hestia]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Vesta (mythology)|Vesta]] || [[File:Hestia Giustiniani.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Goddess of the hearth, fire and of the right ordering of domesticity and the family; she was born into the first Olympian generation and was one of the original twelve Olympians. <br/> She is the first child of Cronus and Rhea, the elder sister of Hades, Demeter, Poseidon, Hera, and Zeus. \n<br/> ''Some lists of the Twelve Olympians omit her in favor of Dionysus, but the speculation that she gave her throne to him in order to keep the peace seems to be modern invention.'' \n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\"|[[Dionysus]] / <br/>[[Bacchus]] || style=\"padding-left:1em;\"| [[Bacchus]] || [[File:Dionysos Louvre Ma87 n2.jpg|75px]] || style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |God of wine, the grape vine, fertility, festivity, ecstasy, madness and resurrection. Patron god of the art of [[theatre]]. <br/> The son of Zeus and the mortal Theban princess [[Semele]]. Married to the Cretan princess [[Ariadne]]. The youngest Olympian god, as well as the only one to have a mortal mother. <br/> His symbols include the grapevine, ivy, cup, tiger, panther, leopard, dolphin, goat, and pinecone.  \n|}\n\n==Genealogy==\n{{chart top|Major Olympians' family tree&nbsp;<ref>This chart is based upon [[Hesiod]]'s ''[[Theogony]]'', unless otherwise noted.</ref>|collapsed=no}}\n{{chart/start}}\n{{chart|}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | |URA |y|GAI |URA=[[Uranus (mythology)|Uranus]]|GAI=[[Gaia (mythology)|Gaia]]}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | |,|-|^|-|.}}\n{{chart|URA| | | | | | | | |CRO |y|RHE |URA=<small>Uranus' genitals</small>|CRO=[[Cronus]]|RHE=[[Rhea (mythology)|Rhea]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|^|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.}}\n{{chart| |!| |ZEU |V|~|~|y|~|HER | |POS | |HAD | |DEM | |HES |ZEU=[[Zeus|'''ZEUS''']]|HER=[[Hera|'''HERA''']]|POS=[[Poseidon|'''POSEIDON''']]|HAD=[[Hades]]|DEM=[[Demeter|'''DEMETER''']]|HES=[[Hestia|'''HESTIA''']]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| |,|^|-|.| |!}}\n{{chart|border=0| |!| | | | |:| |!| |AAA |!|AAA= &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;a <ref>According to [[Homer]], ''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:1.570 1.570&ndash;579],  [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:14.338 14.338], ''[[Odyssey]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-eng1:8.312 8.312], Hephaestus was apparently the son of Hera and Zeus, see Gantz, p. 74.</ref>}}\n{{chart|border=0| |!| | | | |:| |!| | |!|BBB |BBB=&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;b <ref>According to [[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Hes.+Th.+927 927&ndash;929], Hephaestus was produced by Hera alone, with no father, see Gantz, p. 74.</ref>}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| |!| | |!| |!}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:|ARE | |HEP |HEP=[[Hephaestus|'''HEPHAESTUS''']]|ARE=[[Ares|'''ARES''']]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |D|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|~|MET |MET=[[Metis (mythology)|Metis]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| | |ATH |ATH=[[Athena|'''ATHENA''']] <ref>According to [[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Hes.+Th.+886 886&ndash;890], of Zeus' children by his seven wives, Athena was the first to be conceived, but the last to be born; Zeus impregnated Metis then swallowed her, later Zeus himself gave birth to Athena \"from his head\", see Gantz, pp. 51&ndash;52, 83&ndash;84.</ref>}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |D|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|~|LET |LET=[[Leto]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| |,|-|^|-|.}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:|APO | |ART |APO=[[Apollo|'''APOLLO''']]|ART=[[Artemis|'''ARTEMIS''']]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |D|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|~|MAI |MAI=[[Maia (mythology)|Maia]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| | |HER |HER=[[Hermes|'''HERMES''']]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |D|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|~|SEM |SEM=[[Semele]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| | |DIO |DIO=[[Dionysus|'''DIONYSUS''']]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |L|~|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|DIO |DIO=[[Dione (Titaness)|Dione]]}}\n{{chart|border=0|AAA | | | | | | | |BBB|AAA=&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;a <ref>According to [[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Hes.+Th.+183 183&ndash;200], Aphrodite was born from Uranus' severed genitals, see Gantz, pp. 99&ndash;100.</ref>|BBB=&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;b <ref>According to [[Homer]], Aphrodite was the daughter of Zeus (''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:3.374 3.374], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:20.105 20.105]; ''[[Odyssey]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-eng1:8.308 8.308], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-eng1:8.320 320]) and Dione (''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:5.370 5.370&ndash;71]), see Gantz, pp. 99&ndash;100.</ref>}}\n{{chart| |`|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|.| |!}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | |APH |APH=[[Aphrodite|'''APHRODITE''']]}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ancient Greece|Religion}}\n\n* [[Dii Consentes]], the Roman equivalent of the twelve Olympians\n* [[Family tree of the Greek gods]]\n* ''[[Interpretatio graeca]]'', including a table of mythological equivalents\n* [[List of Greek mythological characters]]\n* [[Supreme Council of Ethnikoi Hellenes]]\n* [[Hellenismos]]\n* [[Olympia, Greece|Olympia]]\n* [[Olympians (Marvel Comics)]]\n* [[Olympian Gods (DC Comics)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* [[Walter Burkert|Burkert, Walter]], ''Greek Religion'', [[Harvard University Press]], 1985. {{ISBN|0-674-36281-0}}.\n* Chadwick, John, ''The Mycenaean World'', Cambridge University Press, 1976. {{ISBN|9780521290371}}.\n* Dillon, Matthew, ''Girls and Women in Classical Greek Religion''. London: Routledge. (2002). {{ISBN|0415202728}}.\n* Dowden, Ken, \"Olympian Gods, Olympian Pantheon\", in ''A Companion to Greek Religion'', Daniel Ogden editor, John Wiley & Sons, 2010. {{ISBN|9781444334173}}.\n* Gadbery, Laura M., \"The Sanctuary of the Twelve Gods in the Athenian Agora: A Revised View\", ''Hesperia'' '''61''' (1992), pp.&nbsp;447&ndash;489.\n* Gantz, Timothy, ''Early Greek Myth: A Guide to Literary and